ighly educated, hard working, and often opinionated, E. Maud Graham joined the Canadian contingent of forty teachers. Her eyewitness account reveals the complexity of relations and tensions at a controversial period in the histories of both Britain and South Africa. Graham presents a lively historical travel memoir, and the editors have provided rich political and historical context to her narrative in the Introduction and generous annotations. This is a rare primary source for experts in Colonial Studies, Women’s Studies, and Canadian, South African, and British Imperial History. Readers with an interest in the South African War will be intrigued by Graham’s observations on South African society at the end of the Victorian era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEducationzGreat BritainxColonies. 0aEducationzSouth AfricaxHistory. 0aSouth African War, 1899-1902vPersonal narratives, Canadian. 0aSouth African War, 1899-1902xConcentration campszSouth Africa. 0aSouth African War, 1899-1902xEducation and the war. 0aTeacherszCanadavBiography. 0aTeacherszSouth AfricavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aBritish History.  aEssays.  aSouth African War.  aTravel Memoir.1 aDawson, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGidney, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGraham, E. Maud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlausen, Susanne M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212055440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978177212055442